final_answer("To illustrate the behavior of the `volatile` keyword, you can use a program where multiple threads access a shared variable. Note that unpredictable behavior is heavily dependent on the JVM and hardware.

Example code:
```java
public class VolatileExample implements Runnable {
    private static/*volatile*/ int counter = 0;

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        Thread thread1 = new Thread(new VolatileExample(), "Thread 1");
        Thread thread2 = new Thread(new VolatileExample(), "Thread 2");
        thread1.start();
        thread2.start();
        thread1.join();
        thread2.join();
        System.out.println("The final value of counter is " + counter);
    }

    @Override
    public void run() {
        for(int i=0;i<1000000;i++) {
            incrementCounter();
        }
    }

    private synchronized void incrementCounter() {
        counter++;
    }
}
```
In this case, if you remove `synchronized` and add `volatile`, you may still see incorrect results because `counter++` is not atomic. However, `volatile` ensures that the value is always read from and written to main memory, preventing CPU caching issues. The behavior depends significantly on the hardware (e.g., x86 vs ARM memory models) and JVM optimizations.")
