<code>
final_answer("The best practice for testing multiple implementations of an interface in NUnit is to use inheritance. Define a set of tests that all implementations should pass in an abstract base class, then subclass that for each implementation.

Example implementation:

```csharp
public interface IFoo
{
    bool Bar();
}

public class FooOne : IFoo
{
    public bool Bar() { return true; }
}

public class FooTwo : IFoo
{
    public bool Bar() { return false; }
}

[TestFixture]
public abstract class FooTests
{
    protected IFoo FooUnderTest;

    [SetUp]
    public abstract void Setup();

    [Test]
    public void BarWorksCorrectly()
    {
        Assert.IsTrue(FooUnderTest.Bar());
    }
}

public class FooOneTests : FooTests
{
    public override void Setup()
    {
        FooUnderTest = new FooOne();
    }
}

public class FooTwoTests : FooTests
{
    public override void Setup()
    {
        FooUnderTest = new FooTwo();
    }

    // Override the test if behavior differs for this specific implementation
    [Test]
    public new void BarWorksCorrectly()
    {
        Assert.IsFalse(FooUnderTest.Bar());
    }
}
```

In `FooTests`, you define the common contracts. In `FooOneTests` and `FooTwoTests`, you provide the specific instance via the `Setup` method. This reduces duplication while allowing specific implementations to override or add their own unique test cases.")
