final_answer("To focus or blur a `TextInput` component, you must create a reference (`ref`) to the component and call the `.blur()` or `.focus()` method on that reference. In modern React (v16.3+), this is done using the `useRef` hook in functional components.

Here is the corrected implementation:

```jsx
import React, { useRef, useState } from 'react';
import { TouchableOpacity, View, Text, TextInput } from 'react-native';

export default function App() {
  const textInputRef = useRef(null);
  const [text, setText] = useState("");
  const [typing, setTyping] = useState(false);

  const handleDonePress = () => {
    setTyping(false);
    textInputRef.current.blur();
  }

  return (
   <View>
      <View>
        <Text>Notes</Text>
        {typing && 
        <TouchableOpacity
            onPress={handleDonePress}
        >
            <Text>Done</Text>
        </TouchableOpacity>
        }
   </View>
     <View>
        <TextInput 
            ref={textInputRef}
            multiline={true}
            textAlignVertical='top'
            value={text}
            onChangeText={(text) => setText(text)}
            onFocus={() => setTyping(true)}
        />
    </View>
</View>
  );
}
```

Key changes made:
1. Added `useRef(null)` to create `textInputRef`.
2. Added `ref={textInputRef}` to the `TextInput` component.
3. Created `handleDonePress` which calls `textInputRef.current.blur()` to remove focus from the input.
4. Fixed the `onFocus` prop to use an arrow function `() => setTyping(true)` to prevent it from executing immediately during render.")
